<subSubSection id="C3776556EEFD3B99FF78F89CFF38F871" pageId="428" pageNumber="429" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEEFD3B99FF78F89CFF38F871" blockId="428.[136,778,1805,2070]" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFD3B99FF78F89CFEFBF8AD" bold="true" box="[189,318,1874,1900]" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name refers to the two extremely long setae on the first segment of the female antennule.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3776556EEFD3B9AFF78F879FBE5FF06" lastPageId="431" lastPageNumber="432" pageId="428" pageNumber="429" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD236DDEEFD3B9BFF78F879FB01F871" blockId="428.[136,778,1805,2070]" lastBlockId="430.[810,1452,1942,2070]" lastPageId="430" lastPageNumber="431" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFD3B99FF78F879FE03F810" bold="true" box="[189,454,1975,2001]" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">Descriptionoffemale</emphasis>
. Body (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EEFD3B99FDECF876FD66F813" box="[553,675,1976,2002]" captionStart="FIGURE 284" captionStartId="429.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1350,223,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@429.[200,1388,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="429" captionText="FIGURE 284. Thoracodelphys longiseta sp. nov., female. A, habitus, right; B, urosome, ventral; C, left caudal ramus, ventral; D, rostrum; E, antennule; F, antenna; G, labrum; H, mandible; I, paragnath; J, maxillule. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, D, 0.1 mm; C, E–G, I, J, 0.02 mm; H, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591859/files/figure.png" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">Fig. 284A</figureCitation>
) slightly depressed and moderately inflated: body length 1.40 mm. Prosome 1.02 mmlong, taperinganteriorly, with convex posterior margin: dorsal cephalic shield clearly defined. Metasome with 2 incomplete dorsal sutures marking planes of fusion between first and second, and between second and third pedigerous somites. Third and fourth pedigerous somites completely fused and forming brood pouch. Freeurosome (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EEFD3B99FB42F876FAC5F813" box="[1159,1280,1976,2002]" captionStart="FIGURE 284" captionStartId="429.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1350,223,1845]" captionTargetId="figure-19@429.[200,1388,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="429" captionText="FIGURE 284. Thoracodelphys longiseta sp. nov., female. A, habitus, right; B, urosome, ventral; C, left caudal ramus, ventral; D, rostrum; E, antennule; F, antenna; G, labrum; H, mandible; I, paragnath; J, maxillule. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, D, 0.1 mm; C, E–G, I, J, 0.02 mm; H, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591859/files/figure.png" pageId="428" pageNumber="429">Fig. 284B</figureCitation>
) 5-segmented, tapering posteriorly; genital somite much wider than long, 61×176 μm; 4 abdominalsomites 84×135, 88×116, Maxillule (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EEFF3B9BFECDF858FEB3F871" box="[264,374,1942,1968]" captionStart="FIGURE 294" captionStartId="444.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[240,1350,219,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-20@444.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="444" captionText="FIGURE 294. Bysone bidens sp. nov., female. A, habitus, right; B, urosome, ventral; C, left caudal ramus, ventral; D, rostrum; E, antennule; F, antenna; G, labrum; H, mandible; I, maxillule; J, maxilla. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, 0.1 mm; C, 0.05 mm; D–J, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591883/files/figure.png" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">Fig. 294I</figureCitation>
) armed as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEEFF3B9BFDD9F858FD1BF871" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[540,734,1942,1968]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bysone" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="430" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicaudatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFDD9F858FDE8F86E" box="[540,557,1942,1967]" italics="true" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFD85F858FD1BF871" box="[576,734,1942,1968]" italics="true" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">brevicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFD2DF858FF7CF813" bold="true" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4EEFF3B9BFD2DF858FF7CF813" pageId="430" pageNumber="431" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but seta on coxal endite larger. Maxilla (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EEFF3B9BFD53F876FCC7F813" box="[662,770,1976,2002]" captionStart="FIGURE 294" captionStartId="444.[136,245,1907,1933]" captionTargetBox="[240,1350,219,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-20@444.[194,1392,185,1870]" captionTargetPageId="444" captionText="FIGURE 294. Bysone bidens sp. nov., female. A, habitus, right; B, urosome, ventral; C, left caudal ramus, ventral; D, rostrum; E, antennule; F, antenna; G, labrum; H, mandible; I, maxillule; J, maxilla. Scale bars: A, 0.2 mm; B, 0.1 mm; C, 0.05 mm; D–J, 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591883/files/figure.png" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">Fig. 294J</figureCitation>
) segmented and armed as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6D4D5EEEFF3B9BFE1EF814FD5BF835" authority="Kim &amp; Boxshall, 2020" authorityName="Kim &amp; Boxshall" authorityYear="2020" box="[475,670,2010,2036]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Notodelphyidae" genus="Bysone" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="430" pageNumber="431" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicaudatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFE1EF814FE29F832" box="[475,492,2010,2035]" italics="true" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFDC5F814FD5BF835" box="[512,670,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">brevicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B919EACFEEFF3B9BFD6FF814FCCFF835" bold="true" box="[682,778,2010,2036]" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22A57B4EEFF3B9BFD6FF814FCCFF835" box="[682,778,2010,2036]" pageId="430" pageNumber="431" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Maxilliped (
<figureCitation id="13562A58EEFF3B9BFED6F832FE4CF7D7" box="[275,393,2043,2070]" captionStart="FIGURE 295" captionStartId="445.[136,245,1533,1559]" captionTargetBox="[170,1428,246,1474]" captionTargetId="figure-260@445.[136,1451,221,1499]" captionTargetPageId="445" captionText="FIGURE 295. Bysone bidens sp. nov., female. A, maxilliped; B, leg 1; C, leg 2; D, leg 4; E, leg 5. Scale bars: A, E, 0.02 mm; B–D, 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591885" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591885/files/figure.png" pageId="430" pageNumber="431">Fig. 295A</figureCitation>
) armed with 6 medial setae and 1 outer seta; apex strongly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF126655EEFC3B98FF4DF8BDFD39F813" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4591859" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4591859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4591859/files/figure.png" pageId="429" pageNumber="430" startId="429.[136,245,1907,1933]" targetBox="[256,1350,223,1845]" targetPageId="429">
